For individual User:

#export HISTTIMEFORMAT=" "%D" "%T" "


#export HISTTIMEFORMAT="%H:%M:%S %d-%m-%Y  -->"           OR                 #export HISTTIMEFORMAT="%F %T  -->sour"

To make it permanent run following command:

# vi ~/.bashrc
…………
export HISTTIMEFORMAT="%F %T "



#source  ~/.bashrc

For all profiles:

#vi /etc/profile

#export HISTTIMEFORMAT="%H:%M:%S %d-%m-%Y  -->"            OR                  #export HISTTIMEFORMAT="%F %T  -->"


Time Format

%H The hour in the HH format (for example, 17).
%M The minute in the MM format (for example, 30).
%S The second in the SS format (for example, 24).

%T The full time in the HH:MM:SS format (for example, 17:30:24). This option is equal
to %H:%M:%S

Date Format

%d The day of the month in the DD format (for example, 16).
%m The month in the MM format (for example, 09).
%Y The year in the YYYY format (for example, 2016).
%Z The time zone abbreviation (for example, CEST).

%F The full date in the YYYY-MM-DD format (for example, 2016-09-16). This option
is equal to %Y-%m-%d.


From <https://www.linuxtechi.com/enable-timestamp-history-command/>